article.description: Chasity Melvin scored 17 points and Alana Beard added 16 points Sunday afternoon to lead the Mystics to an 82-62 victory over the Mercury.
article.headline: Mystics shot season-high 48.5 percent
article.linkText: Taurasi sees 4 minutes in Mercury loss to Mystics
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Mystics are filling the void
left by Chamique Holdsclaw, who has missed three of the last four
games with an undisclosed medical condition.

Chasity Melvin scored 17 points and rookie Alana Beard added 16
points and eight rebounds Sunday to lead the Mystics to an 82-62
victory over the Phoenix Mercury.

"Everybody has stepped it up a notch, and that's the big
difference," Melvin said. "Our flow is great out there, which is
unbelievable because a lot of the ladies haven't even played
together more than a minute.

"To see that on the court just goes to show the character of
our team and how we're going to stay together no matter what."

The Mystics have won two straight games without Holdsclaw, the
league's second-leading scorer (19.0). Washington moved 1½ games
behind first-place New York in the tight Eastern Conference.

Stacey Dales-Schuman added 14 points and four assists for the
Mystics, who shot a season-high 48.5 percent. Beard, the No. 2 pick
in the WNBA draft, went 3-for-3 from 3-point range.

"This is Alana Beard," Dales-Schuman said. "I've seen her do
some things in the last couple of games that I haven't seen a lot
of women do, honestly. She's phenomenal. She's getting everybody
involved and that's the mark of a great player."

Holdsclaw missed a game at Charlotte on July 24 because of
personal and medical reasons. She returned four days later for a
loss to Detroit, then announced she would miss the next two games
before the WNBA takes a monthlong break for the Olympics.

"We're still very concerned about Chamique and wish she could
share this with us because it's important that we're playing like
this and doing so well," Dales-Schuman said. "To have her not be
a part of that is frustrating because she's been a part of this
franchise for six years.

"Chamique is itching to get back with us, I can tell you that
much. I think she's going to look at this and come back with fire
and motivation and a joy to play again with us."

Penny Taylor scored 16 points and Gwen Jackson added 11 to lead
the Mercury. Former Mystic Nikki McCray and Anna DeForge each
scored eight points.

The Mystics went on an 8-0 run early in the second half, capped
by Beard's two free throws for a 55-36 lead with 15:58 left. The
Mercury came within 66-55 on McCray's 3-pointer, but got no closer.

Phoenix rookie Diana Taurasi, slowed by a hip pointer injury,
played only four minutes and did not shoot.

"If she could play, believe me, she would have been out
there," Mercury coach Carrie Graf said. "But she couldn't move
and so we have to move on without her."

Taurasi, a member of the USA Olympic team, will play in the
All-Stars vs Olympians at Radio City Music Hall in New York on
August 5.
